The {{ill|Kamitsukeno clan|ja|上毛野氏|1=Kamitsukeno clan|12=draft|12=draft}} is mentioned in several parts of the {{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|12=draft|12=draft}}, including the story of {{ill|Toyokiirihiko-no-mikoto|ja|豊城入彦命|1=Toyokiirihiko-no-Mikoto|1=Toyokiirihiko-no-Mikoto|12=draft|12=draft}}, the eldest son of Emperor {{ill|Suijin|ja|崇神天皇|12=draft|12=draft}}, and his dream<ref>{{Nihon Shoki|Suijin 48th year, 1st month, 10th day}}</ref>, as well as the story of his grandson {{ill|Hikosasima no Ō|ja|彦狭嶋王|12=draft|12=draft}} being dispatched along the {{ill|Tōsandō|ja|東山道|12=draft|12=draft}}<ref name="#1">{{Nihon Shoki|Keikō 55th year, 2nd month, 5th day}}</ref> and his son {{ill|Mimorowake no Ō|ja|御諸別王|1=Mimorowake|12=draft|12=draft}} managing the eastern provinces<ref name="#1"/>. The {{ill|Shinsen Shōjiroku|ja|新撰姓氏録|1=Shinsen Shōjiroku|12=draft|12=draft}} also states that the Kamitsukeno and {{ill|Shimotsukeno Clan|ja|下毛野氏|1=Shimotsukeno clan|lt=Shimotsukeno clan|12=draft|12=draft}} were of the same lineage.

Wakako appears in the Nihon Shoki during the 2nd year of [[Emperor Tenji]] (663), in March, where it states:
{{quotation|The front general {{ill|Kamitsukeno no Wakako|ja|上毛野君稚子|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Hashihito no Muraji Ōfuta|ja|間人大蓋|12=draft|12=draft}}, middlegenerals {{ill|Kose no Kamusaki no Omi Osamu|ja|巨勢神前訳語|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Miwa no Kimi Nemaro|ja|三輪根麻呂|12=draft|12=draft}}, and rear generals {{ill|Abe no Hiketa no Omi Hirafu|ja|阿倍比羅夫|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Ōyake no Omi Kamatsuka|ja|大宅臣鎌柄|12=draft|12=draft}} were sent with 27,000 troops to attack {{ill|Silla|ja|新羅|12=draft|12=draft}}.<ref>{{Nihon Shoki|Tenji 2nd year, 3rd month}}</ref>}}

By June of the same year, the generals' forces achieved victory:
{{quotation|They captured two fortresses at {{ill|Sabikinue|ja|沙鼻岐奴江|12=draft|12=draft}}.<ref>{{Nihon Shoki|Tenji 2nd year, 6th month}}</ref>}}

However, the exact location of "Sabikinue" is debated. If it corresponds to "Sabi" in modern {{ill|Sangju|ja|尚州市|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|North Gyeongsang Province|ja|慶尚北道|12=draft|12=draft}}, the invasion likely came from the west. Alternatively, if it corresponds to "Sangi" in {{ill|Sangju|ja|三嘉|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|South Gyeongsang Province|ja|慶尚南道|12=draft|12=draft}}, the invasion may have originated from the south.

The decisive battle of {{ill|Baekgang|ja|白村江|12=draft|12=draft}} against the {{ill|Tang-Silla Alliance|ja|唐・新羅連合軍|12=draft|12=draft}} occurred two months later.<ref>{{Nihon Shoki|Tenji 2nd year, 8th month, 27th-28th days}}</ref> Wakako’s role in this final battle and his fate remain unknown.

In the 13th year of Emperor {{ill|Tenmu|ja|Emperor Tenmu|1=Emperor Tenmu|12=draft|12=draft}} (684), the {{ill|Eight Kabane|ja|八色の姓|1=Eight Kabane system|12=draft|12=draft}} were established, and the Kamitsukeno Clan received the title of {{ill|Ason|ja|朝臣|12=draft|12=draft}} in recognition of their longstanding contributions to the court, including the service of {{ill|Kamitsukeno no Mikoto no Miko no Mitsumaro|ja|上毛野三千|12=draft|12=draft}}.<ref>{{Nihon Shoki|Tenmu 13th year, 11th month, 1st day}}</ref>

